---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import styles from "./docs.module.css";
---

<Base title="Docs — Lucid" description="Introduction and installation for Lucid.">
  <div class={styles.pageHeader}>
    <h1>Docs</h1>
    <p class={styles.pageHeaderLede}>
      Everything you need to install Lucid and understand how it composes with
      the rest of your stack.
    </p>
  </div>

  <lucid-tabs label="Docs sections" value="introduction" orientation="vertical">
    <lucid-tab slot="tab" value="introduction">Introduction</lucid-tab>
    <lucid-tab slot="tab" value="installation">Installation</lucid-tab>

    <lucid-tab-panel value="introduction" class={styles.prose}>
      <h2>What Lucid is</h2>
      <p>
        Lucid is a design system distributed as Web Components. Every component
        is a native custom element that any framework — or plain HTML — can
        render without wrappers or hydration. Behind the scenes, each component
        uses Shadow DOM for style isolation and CSS custom properties for
        theming.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Web Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Framework-agnostic by construction.</strong> If a browser can
          parse HTML, it can render a Lucid component.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Style-isolated by default.</strong> Shadow DOM prevents
          outer CSS from leaking in and component CSS from leaking out.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Themable via tokens.</strong> Every component reads CSS
          custom properties like <code>--lucid-color-primary</code>. Override
          on any ancestor and the change cascades.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Accessibility &amp; internationalization</h2>
      <p>
        Every shipped component passes axe-core at WCAG 2.1 AA and has
        committed baseline screenshots in both LTR and RTL. Physical CSS
        properties (<code>margin-left</code>, <code>float: right</code>) are
        rejected by CI. Focus, keyboard interaction, and ARIA state are part
        of the contract, not an afterthought.
      </p>
    </lucid-tab-panel>

    <lucid-tab-panel value="installation" class={styles.prose}>
      <h2>Install</h2>
      <pre class={styles.proseCode}>bun add @mind-matrix/lucid-components</pre>

      <h2>Load the tokens (optional)</h2>
      <p>
        The components render fine without tokens, but you'll want the
        defaults for a real look.
      </p>
      <pre class={styles.proseCode}>{`<link
  rel="stylesheet"
  href="@mind-matrix/lucid-core/tokens.css"
/>`}</pre>

      <h2>Import once at your app entry</h2>
      <pre class={styles.proseCode}>import "@mind-matrix/lucid-components";</pre>

      <h2>Use anywhere</h2>
      <pre class={styles.proseCode}>{`<lucid-button variant="primary">Save</lucid-button>

<lucid-card variant="elevated">
  <h3 slot="title">Card title</h3>
  <p>Slots take any HTML.</p>
</lucid-card>`}</pre>

      <h2>Framework notes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>React (17+).</strong> Plain <code>onClick</code> works on
          <code>&lt;lucid-button&gt;</code> because it dispatches native
          <code>click</code> events. For components that dispatch custom
          events, install <code>@mind-matrix/lucid-react</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Vue.</strong> Add <code>isCustomElement</code> matching
          <code>lucid-*</code> to your Vue compiler options once.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Angular.</strong> Add <code>CUSTOM_ELEMENTS_SCHEMA</code>
          to the module or component that uses <code>&lt;lucid-*&gt;</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Astro / vanilla / Svelte / Solid.</strong> Nothing to
          configure.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </lucid-tab-panel>
  </lucid-tabs>
</Base>
